HB 590 Engrossed 2026 Regular Session Glorioso
Abstract: Establishes the "Green Envelope Program" and the "Blue Envelope Program" for
improving traffic stop communication between law enforcement and those with
mental disabilities and autism spectrum disorder.
Present law authorizes the Dept. of Public Safety and Corrections (DPS&C), office of motor
vehicles (OMV), to issue identification stickers or decals to symbolize awareness for certain
disabilities, at no cost to the driver or parent or legal guardian.
Proposed law requires the DPS&C, OMV, to create specially designed envelopes to be
provided to drivers with mental, physical, developmental disabilities, or autism spectrum
disorder, or their parents or legal guardians, that provide proof as required by present law.
Specifies that the envelopes include guidelines to assist officers in recognizing and
effectively communicating with drivers with disabilities during traffic stops.
Proposed law requires the DPS&C, OMV, to create green envelopes to be provided to
drivers with mental disabilities, their parents, or guardians.
Proposed law specifies that the green envelopes must have guidelines on the exterior to
instruct law enforcement on how to approach and effectively communicate with drivers with
mental disabilities.
Proposed law allows for these drivers to keep essential documents, such as driver's licenses,
vehicle registrations, contact cards, and medical documents in the green envelopes.
Proposed law allows drivers with mental disabilities, their parents, or guardians the ability
to obtain the green envelopes without providing medical documentation.
Proposed law requires the OMV to create blue envelopes to be provided to drivers with
autism spectrum disorder, or their parents or guardians.
Proposed law specifies that the blue envelopes must have guidelines on the exterior to
instruct law enforcement on how to approach and effectively communicate with drivers with
autism spectrum disorder.
Proposed law allows for these drivers to keep essential documents, such as driver's licenses,
vehicle registrations, contact cards, and medical documents in the blue envelope.
Proposed law allows drivers with autism spectrum disorder, or their parents or guardians,
the ability to obtain the blue envelopes without providing medical documentation.
Effective Jan. 1, 2027.
(Adds R.S. 32:403.2.1, 403.3(B)(2)(c), and 403.3.1)
